> 6
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
â€¢â€¢Grouping Operatorâ€¢â€¢
â€¢â€¢ Basically a way to group an expression, or to override.â€¢â€¢â€¢
â€¢â€¢Example of Grouping Operator:

2 + 2 * 4;
> 10

( 2 + 2 ) * 4;
> 16

let myVariable = ( 2 + 2 );

myVariable;
> 4
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
â€¢â€¢type coercionâ€¢â€¢
â€¢â€¢Type coercion refers to the automatic or implicit conversion of values from one data type to another. This often happens in programming languages when an operation involves operands of different data types, and the language attempts to make them compatible.â€¢â€¢

â€¢â€¢In this example, if we add a # to a string value in a  Python, the result is an error. But JavaScript can help fix/bypass this with coercion:

>>> "1" + 1
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
TypeError: cannot concatenate 'str' and 'int' objects

â€¢â€¢Instead of jS returning this error. It uses coercion:

"1" + 1;
> "11"


â€¢â€¢ We can also do this with <data types>:

let myVariable = 333;

typeof myVariable;
> "number"

myVariable = myVariable.toString();
> "333"

typeof myVariable;
> "string"
